Identified hadron spectra. Experiment with a tracker and a particle identification system (based on specific energy loss, time-of-flight, Cherenkov cone angle, etc.) can discriminate individual hadron species track-by-track. Measured are then either yield ratios or identified hadron spectra, the product of relative yields and charged particle spectra. Only ALICE and LHCb have been specifically designed with particle identification capabilities, but CMS has successfully used the energy deposits in its tracker to identify particles with p<2GeVc−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
